    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i get that it goes to interest first but it feels like there's some kind of hidden drag on my payments. like why does it feel like the interest is actively working against me to keep the balance high? is there some specific math that explains why it feels so sneaky?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, there is a specific math formula at play here, and it can indeed feel like a sneaky little goblin under your bed, always ready to jump out and surprise you. The interest on your student loan is calculated using the formula I = P x R x T, where I is the interest, P is the principal balance, R is the annual interest rate, and T is the time period in years. \n\nEach month, the interest is calculated on the remaining principal balance, which means that as you pay down the principal, the interest you pay each month decreases. It's like a game of whack-a-mole, where the moles (interest) are always popping up, even as you whack (pay) them down. The interest is calculated on the remaining balance, so as you pay down the principal, the interest is calculated on a smaller and smaller amount, which can feel like it's working against you. \n\nBut don't worry, it's not really working against you – it's just the way the math works. It's like trying to catch a slippery fish with a net – the fish (principal) keeps moving, but the net (interest) is always trying to catch up. It's just a matter of understanding the math behind it",
      "source": "target",
